day 46 of crew maitrix : simple C program that checks whether a given number is two digits or three digits and displays an appropriate message.

IN C :

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int num;

    // Input the number
    printf("Enter a number: ");
    scanf("%d", &num);

    // Check for two-digit number
    if (num >= 10 && num <= 99) {
        printf("%d is a two-digit number.\n", num);
    }
    // Check for three-digit number
    else if (num >= 100 && num <= 999) {
        printf("%d is a three-digit number.\n", num);
    }
    // If the number is neither two nor three digits
    else {
        printf("%d is neither a two-digit nor a three-digit number.\n", num);
    }

    return 0;
}

IN PYTHON:

# Input the number from the user
num = int(input("Enter a number: "))

# Check for two-digit number
if 10 <= num <= 99:
    print(f"{num} is a two-digit number.")

# Check for three-digit number
elif 100 <= num <= 999:
    print(f"{num} is a three-digit number.")

# If the number is neither two nor three digits
else:
    print(f"{num} is neither a two-digit nor a three-digit number.")

O/P :

Enter a number: 56
56 is a two-digit number.

Enter a number: 234
234 is a three-digit number.

Enter a number: 5
5 is neither a two-digit nor a three-digit number.
